The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Theni, June 7 (PTI): Teachers of a Tamil Nadu school, beaten up by guardians after poor results by their wards, have said the results would have been better if they were allowed to spank unruly pupils.           
	Villagers thrashed two government school teachers at Kottur near Theni in Tamil Nadu after only 20 per cent students passed the Class X exam. An official of the teachers association said the teachers could not impose discipline because the government had banned corporal punishment in schools.                  
	Nagpur (PTI): A Maharashtra high court bench has directed the state government to submit an action plan to overcome the threat to safety of passengers and aircraft caused by stray animals at the Dr Ambedkar International Airport.                   
	London (PTI): Sixteen Indians have been arrested for working in England without work permits. The Indians, including 12 women, used to plant, pick and prepare salad onions for a firm in Evesham in south west England.                   
	Noida (PTI): A domestic help poisoned four members of a family in Noida and fled with cash and jewellery, police said on Saturday. Ajay, his wife Sandhya and their children Rakshak and Tara were taken to hospital where Sandhya was declared dead. The servant, Akash, is still at large.                   
	Madurai (PTI): Three police sniffer dogs fought a snake and killed it on Friday but suffered serious bites. They are stable in hospital.                  
	 Nasik (PTI): Police arrested three youths on Friday for allegedly preparing fake visa and other documents. Salim Amar Shaikh, Zahir Shaikh and Shyam Mali had allegedly swindled one Jaspalsingh Tarasingh Rupwal by preparing a fake visa for him and falsely promising him a job with Khushbu Industries in Dubai.                                                                                                                         
